#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:1
msgid "The `?` operator for easier error handling"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.13](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.13-brightgreen.svg) for `Result<T, E>`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:5
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.22](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.22-brightgreen.svg) for `Option<T>`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:7
msgid ""
"Rust has gained a new operator, `?`, that makes error handling more pleasant "
"by reducing the visual noise involved. It does this by solving one simple "
"problem. To illustrate, imagine we had some code to read some data from a "
"file:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:15
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:49
#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:73
msgid "\"username.txt\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:31
msgid ""
"Note: this code could be made simpler with a single call to [`std::fs::"
"read_to_string`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std/fs/fn.read_to_string."
"html), but we're writing it all out manually here to have an example with "
"multiple errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:36
msgid ""
"This code has two paths that can fail, opening the file and reading the data "
"from it. If either of these fail to work, we'd like to return an error from "
"`read_username_from_file`. Doing so involves `match`ing on the result of the "
"I/O operations. In simple cases like this though, where we are only "
"propagating errors up the call stack, the matching is just boilerplate - "
"seeing it written out, in the same pattern every time, doesn't provide the "
"reader with a great deal of useful information."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:44
msgid "With `?`, the above code looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:58
msgid ""
"The `?` is shorthand for the entire match statements we wrote earlier. In "
"other words, `?` applies to a `Result` value, and if it was an `Ok`, it "
"unwraps it and gives the inner value. If it was an `Err`, it returns from "
"the function you're currently in. Visually, it is much more straightforward. "
"Instead of an entire match statement, now we are just using the single \"?\" "
"character to indicate that here we are handling errors in the standard way, "
"by passing them up the call stack."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:66
msgid ""
"Seasoned Rustaceans may recognize that this is the same as the `try!` macro "
"that's been available since Rust `1.0`. And indeed, they are the same. "
"Previously, `read_username_from_file` could have been implemented like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:82
msgid ""
"So why extend the language when we already have a macro? There are multiple "
"reasons. First, `try!` has proved to be extremely useful, and is used often "
"in idiomatic Rust. It is used so often that we think it's worth having a "
"sweet syntax. This sort of evolution is one of the great advantages of a "
"powerful macro system: speculative extensions to the language syntax can be "
"prototyped and iterated on without modifying the language itself, and in "
"return, macros that turn out to be especially useful can indicate missing "
"language features. This evolution, from `try!` to `?` is a great example."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:91
msgid ""
"One of the reasons `try!` needs a sweeter syntax is that it is quite "
"unattractive when multiple invocations of `try!` are used in succession. "
"Consider:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:99
msgid "as opposed to"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:105
msgid ""
"The first is quite difficult to scan visually, and each layer of error "
"handling prefixes the expression with an additional call to `try!`. This "
"brings undue attention to the trivial error propagation, obscuring the main "
"code path, in this example the calls to `foo`, `bar` and `baz`. This sort of "
"method chaining with error handling occurs in situations like the builder "
"pattern."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:112
msgid ""
"Finally, the dedicated syntax will make it easier in the future to produce "
"nicer error messages tailored specifically to `?`, whereas it is difficult "
"to produce nice errors for macro-expanded code generally."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/error-handling-and-panics/the-question-mark-operator-for-easier-error-handling.md:116
msgid ""
"You can use `?` with `Result<T, E>`s, but also with `Option<T>`. In that "
"case, `?` will return a value for `Some(T)` and return `None` for `None`. "
"One current restriction is that you cannot use `?` for both in the same "
"function, as the return type needs to match the type you use `?` on. In the "
"future, this restriction will be lifted."
msgstr ""
